            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this interest-only loan calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool models a classic interest-only loan: for the first few
                years you pay only interest, then the loan converts to a fully
                amortizing principal-and-interest loan for the remaining term.
              </p>
              <p>We calculate in three steps:</p>
              <ol>
                <li>Compute the monthly interest-only payment.</li>
                <li>
                  Compute the principal-and-interest payment after the
                  interest-only period.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Generate a full amortization schedule, including any extra
                  principal you choose to pay.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>1. Interest-only payment formula</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Monthly interest-only payment</strong></p>
                <p>Let:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( P \) = loan principal (amount borrowed)</li>
                  <li>
                    \( r \) = annual interest rate (decimal, e.g. 6% = 0.06)
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p>Monthly interest rate: \( i = \dfrac{r}{12} \)</p>
                <p>
                  Interest-only payment: \[ \text{Payment}_{IO} = P \times i \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Example: on a \$300,000 loan at 6%: \[ i = 0.06 / 12 = 0.005 \]
                \[ \text{Payment}_{IO} = 300{,}000 \times 0.005 = 1{,}500 \]
              </p>

              <h3>2. Payment after the interest-only period</h3>
              <p>
                After the interest-only period ends, the remaining balance
                (usually still the original principal) must be repaid over the
                remaining years.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Standard amortizing payment</strong></p>
                <p>Let:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    \( N \) = number of remaining months after the interest-only
                    period
                  </li>
                  <li>\( i \) = monthly interest rate as above</li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Payment}_{PI} = P \times \frac{i(1+i)^N}{(1+i)^N - 1}
                  \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator uses this formula to show how much your payment
                will jump once principal repayment begins.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Extra principal payments</h3>
              <p>
                Many borrowers use interest-only loans but still pay extra
                toward principal. In this calculator you can add a fixed extra
                principal amount each month. We:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Apply the extra payment immediately to reduce the balance.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Recalculate interest on the lower balance for the next month.
                </li>
                <li>Stop the schedule once the balance reaches zero.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                This lets you see how much faster you can pay off the loan and
                how much interest you save compared with making only the
                required payments.
              </p>

              <h2>Interest-only vs principal-and-interest loans</h2>
              <p>
                An <strong>interest-only loan</strong> is one where, for a
                defined introductory period, your required payments cover only
                the interest charged on the outstanding balance. The principal
                does not decrease unless you make extra payments.
              </p>
              <p>Compared with a standard principal-and-interest loan:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Pros:</strong> lower required payments at the start,
                  more cash flow flexibility.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Cons:</strong> higher payments later, more total
                  interest, and no equity build-up during the interest-only
                  phase (except from market appreciation).
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Typical use cases</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Property investors expecting to sell or refinance before
                  principal is due.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Borrowers with variable income (e.g. bonuses, commissions) who
                  plan lump-sum principal payments.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Short-term cash flow needs where lower payments are critical
                  in the early years.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Risks to consider</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Payment shock:</strong> when the interest-only period
                  ends, the new payment can be significantly higher.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Negative equity risk:</strong> if property values
                  fall, you may owe more than the home is worth because you have
                  not reduced the balance.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Refinancing risk:</strong> you may not qualify to
                  refinance if your income or credit worsens, or if lending
                  standards tighten.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>How to read the amortization schedule</h2>
              <p>The schedule table shows each monthly payment broken into:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Payment:</strong> the required payment (interest-only
                  or principal-and-interest).
                </li>
                <li><strong>Interest:</strong> interest charged that month.</li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Principal:</strong> how much of the required payment
                  reduces the balance.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Extra:</strong> any additional principal you chose to
                  pay.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Balance:</strong> remaining loan balance after all
                  payments that month.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                During the interest-only period, the <em>Principal</em> column
                will be zero unless you add extra payments. Once the
                interest-only period ends, the principal portion grows over time
                while the interest portion gradually declines.
              </p>

              <h2>When an interest-only loan can make sense</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  You have a clear, realistic plan to repay or refinance before
                  the higher payments begin.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Your income is high and stable, and you understand the risks.
                </li>
                <li>
                  You are an experienced investor using leverage with a
                  conservative buffer for rate rises.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                If you are unsure, compare the total interest and payment jump
                in this calculator with a standard loan (set the interest-only
                period to 0) and consider getting independent financial advice.
              </p>
            </section>

            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>How long can an interest-only period last?</h3>
              <p>
                It depends on the lender and product. Common interest-only
                periods are 3, 5, 7 or 10 years on a 25–30 year mortgage.
                Regulations in some countries limit how long you can stay
                interest-only or require a credible repayment plan.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Does an interest-only loan always convert to
                principal-and-interest?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Most modern interest-only mortgages are structured as adjustable
                or fixed-rate loans that automatically convert to
                principal-and-interest after the interest-only period. Some
                older or specialist products may require a balloon payment
                instead. Always read your loan contract carefully.
              </p>

              <h3>
                What if I sell the property during the interest-only period?
              </h3>
              <p>
                When you sell, the outstanding loan balance is repaid from the
                sale proceeds. If the sale price is higher than the balance, you
                keep the equity (minus selling costs). If it is lower, you may
                need to bring cash to closing.
              </p>

              <h3>How can I reduce the risk of an interest-only loan?</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Keep a cash buffer for rate rises and vacancies (for
                  investment property).
                </li>
